{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1486"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1486"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.35,0.22,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111592"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93679"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"781"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"2197"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111592"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner complaining of pain in the second toe of his right foot. The pain commenced 24 hours ago during football training and has gradually increased in intensity since then. He is unable to remember if he had sustained trauma to the area. Paracetamol has had a minimal effect on the pain. He is healthy and does not have any medical conditions. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 115/70 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2C. The patient has a slight antalgic gait, though his right foot is neurovascularly intact. There is some discolouration underneath the nailbed of the 2nd distal phalange extending to its most distal aspect (image). The aforementioned area is tender to palpation while the rest of the foot has no other abnormalities warranting further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nail biopsy","Oral antibiotics","Simple analgesia","Surgical removal of the nail plate","Trephination"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a subungual haematoma, a collection of blood underneath the nail secondary to trauma. No treatment is required in the majority of cases. In light of this patient\u0027s worsening pain, draining the blood and relieving the pressure under his nail as soon as possible will provide the patient with instant relief. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pain can be relieved by \u003Cstrong\u003Etrephination \u003C/strong\u003Edrainage using a sharp needle or a heated paper clip to gently penetrate the nail, usually performed within 48 hours of the injury. The nail should subsequently covered with a sterile dressing and kept dry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENail biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered if there is suspicion of subungual melanoma. Unlike melanoma, nail discolouration from the haematoma will gradually clear as the nail heals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Eare not appropriate as there are no other signs or symptoms of an infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver-the-counter \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as an adjunct therapy, but will ultimately not address the root cause of the pain (i.e. pressure under the nail).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical removal of the nail plate \u003C/strong\u003E(avulsion) is not required. Some indications for this include severe ingrown toenails or nail bed injuries - not present in this patient. If it were required, surgical removal could be performed in the Emergency Department or General Practice setting. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subungual haematomas can resolve on their own without medical intervention. However, they can be drained to relieve the pressure if there is acute pain."],"references":["Pingel C, McDowell C. Subungual Hematoma Drainage. [Updated 2021 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482508/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93679"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1486"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16261"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16261"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd625eb0-3633-46b9-9bc5-9eb620b014dc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd625eb0-3633-46b9-9bc5-9eb620b014dc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":580,"height":435}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93679"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T11:23:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T11:23:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1486"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111592"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relati